SIMPLE: recollection
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Recollection
<hw>Rec`ol*lec"tion</hw> <pr>(r?k`?l*l?k"sh?n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Cf. F. <ets>r⟦eacute⟧collection</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
act of recollecting, or recalling to the memory; the operation by which
objects are recalled to the memory, or ideas revived in the mind;
reminiscence; remembrance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The power of recalling ideas to the mind, or the
period within which things can be recollected; remembrance; memory;
<as>as, an event within my <ex>recollection</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is recollected; something called to mind;
reminiscence.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧One of his earliest
<xex>recollections</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The act or practice of collecting or concentrating
the mind; concentration; self-control.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From such an education Charles contracted habits of gravity and
<qex>recollection</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Robertson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Reminiscence; remembrance. See
<er>Memory</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Recollective</ent>⟦br⟧
